Answer:
Sure, I can provide an outline for an 1850-word horror story in a LaTeX document format. Here's a possible outline:
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}
\title{The Haunted House}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle
\section{Act I: Introduction}
\subsection{Opening Scene}
The story opens with a description of an old, abandoned house on the outskirts of town. The house is dilapidated and overgrown with weeds, and has been empty for years. The camera zooms in on a broken window, through which we can see a dark, dusty interior.
\subsection{Characters}
We are introduced to the main character, a young woman named Sarah, who has recently moved to town. She is curious about the old house and decides to explore it. As she approaches the house, she meets a neighbor, an old man named Mr. Johnson, who warns her about the house and tells her that it's haunted. Sarah is skeptical but intrigued.
\subsection{Setting}
The setting is a small town in the middle of nowhere. The town is surrounded by forests and hills, and the old house is located on the outskirts of town, at the end of a dirt road.
\subsection{Inciting Incident}
Sarah decides to explore the old house, despite Mr. Johnson's warning. She enters the house and begins to explore the dusty, cobweb-filled rooms. As she wanders through the house, she begins to feel a sense of unease. She hears strange noises and feels as if she's being watched.
\subsection{Plot Point 1}
As Sarah explores the house, she comes across a room that seems to be frozen in time. The room is immaculate, as if it has been untouched for decades. In the center of the room is an old dollhouse, which Sarah finds oddly familiar. As she examines the dollhouse, she begins to feel a sense of dread.
\section{Act II: Rising Action}
\subsection{Flashback}
The story flashes back to Sarah's childhood. We see her playing with a dollhouse that looks exactly like the one she found in the old house. She is playing with her sister, Emily, who suddenly disappears. Sarah searches for Emily but can't find her. The flashback ends.
\subsection{Supernatural Elements}
As Sarah continues to explore the old house, she begins to see ghostly apparitions. She sees a young girl who looks like Emily, as well as other ghostly figures. She hears voices and footsteps, but can't find the source.
\subsection{Plot Point 2}
Sarah discovers a hidden room in the old house. The room is filled with old toys and dolls, including the dollhouse from her childhood. As she examines the dolls, she realizes that they are all replicas of people she knows, including Mr. Johnson and other townspeople. She begins to feel as if the dolls are watching her.
\subsection{Non-Linear Narrative}
The story becomes more non-linear, with flashbacks and dream sequences interwoven with the present-day action. Sarah begins to have nightmares about the old house and the dolls.
\subsection{Climax}
The climax of the story occurs when Sarah discovers the source of the supernatural activity in the old house. She finds a hidden room filled with old newspapers and documents, which reveal that the previous owner of the house was a dollmaker who used real human hair and skin to make his dolls. The dolls are possessed by the spirits of the people whose hair and skin were used.
\section{Act III: Resolution}
\subsection{Confrontation}
Sarah confronts the spirits of the dolls and the dollmaker. She realizes that the only way to stop the haunting is to destroy the dolls and the dollhouse.
\subsection{Resolution}
Sarah destroys the dolls and the dollhouse, and the haunting stops. She leaves the old house and never returns. The story ends with a shot of the old house, now empty and silent.
\end{document} **Finished.**

